==(Canadian) English==
===Alternative spellings===
* [[neighborhood]]
===Pronunciation===
\Neigh"bor*hood\
===Etymology===
[[neighbour]] + [[-hood]]
===Noun===
[[Category:English nouns]]
'''neighbourhood'''
#The quality or condition of being a neighbour; the state of  being or dwelling near; proximity.
#:'''quotations''':
#:*"Then the prison and the palace were in awful [neighbourhood]." &mdash; [[w:Edward Bulwer-Lytton, 1st Baron Lytton|Lord Lytton]].
#A place near; vicinity; adjoining district; a region the inhabitants of which may be counted as neighbours
#:'''examples''':
#:''He lives in my neighbourhood.''
#The inhabitants who live in the vicinity of each other
#:'''examples''':
#:''The fire alarmed all the neighbourhood.''
#(''obsolete'') The disposition becoming a neighbour; neighbourly kindness or good will. 
#:'''quotations''':
#:*"" &mdash;[[w:Jeremy Taylor|Jeremy Taylor]].
====Synonyms====
* [[vicinity]]
* [[proximity]]

====Related terms====
* [[microneighbourhood]]

====Usage note====
[[Neighbourhood]] is Anglo-Saxon, and [[vicinity]] is Latin. [[Vicinity]] does not commonly denote as close a connection as [[neighbourhood]] does.  A neighbourhood is a more immediately vicinity. The houses immediately adjoining a square are in the neighbourhood of that square; those which are somewhat further removed are also in the vicinity of the square.

